------------------------------------------------------------------------


idump = 1 to write an ascii file of some of the seg-y header values
        2 to write an ascii file of most of the seg-y header values

tstart - the trace start time (s) of the seg-y data; tstart is an array,
         each element corresponding in order to the seg-y files which
         are read in for conversion

nbytes - number of bytes per word for the seg-y data (if set incorrectly 
         in the headers 

npts0 - number of points (only use this if you suspect it is set wrong
        in the seg-y header) 

npick - the number of pick header words to create for the z-format data 
        (this determines how many picks can be made for each trace)

src = "r" for common-receiver gather data (otherwise common-shot is assumed)

itype - used to select only specific traces from seg-y file using a 
        user-supplied "itype" file

dfile - name of output data file containing z-format data

hfile - name of output header file corresponding to z-format data in dfile

iout = 1 to write the data in z-format and create the header file

nfile - the number of distinct seg-y files to be converted into one 
        z-format file 

vred0 - the reducing velocity (km/s) of the original seg-y data

vred - the reducing velocity (km/s) of the z-format data

tmin, tmax - the minimum and maximum trace time (s) of the z-format data

omit0 - omit dead traces (i.e., traces containing all zero values)

xmax - omit traces with offsets (km) greater than xmax 

omax - print a warning message indicating all traces which have offsets
       in their seg-y headers which are different from the calculated
       value by more than omax 

iocalc = 1 to calculate the shot-receiver offset using the shot and
           receiver positions specified in the seg-y headers; otherwise
           the offset already in the seg-y is used

itcorrect = 1 to add the time delay in the seg-y header to the trace  
              start time
           -1 to subtract the time delay in the seg-y hearder to the trace
              start time
           (itcorrect is an array, each element corresponding in order to 
            the seg-y files which are read in for conversion)

fmt = 'int' - trace values are read and written as 2 byte integers.
      'sun' - trace values are read and written as 4 byte IEEE reals.
      'ibm' - trace values are read as 4 byte IBM reals and written
              as 4 byte IEEE reals.

nt1, nt2 - the first and last trace in each seg-y file to convert to
           z-format

cm - central meridian (degrees, positive for east) for calculation of
     utm coordinates using iutm=1

x0, y0, x00, y00, rot - used to shift and rotate the utm coordinates into 
                        any position and orientation according to the 
                        equation:

        xutm'=(xutm-x0)*cos(rot)-(yutm-y0)*sin(rot)+x00
        yutm'=(xutm-x0)*sin(rot)+(yutm-y0)*cos(rot)+y00

        where xutm and yutm are the utm coordinates obtained from the
        latitude and longitude in the seg-y header, and xutm' and yutm'
        are the transformed coordinates

iutm = 1 to calculate utm (x,y cartesian) coordinates given the latitude
       and longitude values in the seg-y hearders

xumin, xumax, yumin, yumax - omit traces with transformed utm coordinates
                             that fall outside the box defined by xumin,
                             xumax, yumin, yumax 

tbulk - a bulk time shift (s) to be applied to all traces; tbulk is an 
        array, each element corresponding in order to the seg-y files 
        which are read in for conversion

rdepth - set the receiver depth to this value (m) 

resamp = 1 to decimate data by a factor of two

nrecord - force this number of traces per record in the output file

cfact - the seg-y header words containing latitudes and longitudes
        are divided by cfact to obtain values in degrees 

--------------------------

The following are specialized parameters that can be ignored:

numread -
nchange - 
clat - 
clong - 
xlatlong - 
xelev - 
xutm - 

